A configuration that mitigates sensitivity to $\beta$ and $V_{B E}$ is depicted in Fig. 5.19. Here, resistor $R_{E}$ is placed in series with the emitter, reducing sensitivity to $V_{B E}$. Intuitively, this happens because $R_{E}$ has a linear I-V relationship, unlike an exponential one. Thus, errors in $V_{X}$ due to inaccuracies in $R_{1}$, $R_{2}$, or $V_{C C}$ are partly offset by $R_{E}$, resulting in smaller errors in $V_{B E}$ and hence $I_{C}$. This technique, known as "emitter degeneration," modifies several circuit characteristics, as discussed later in this chapter.

