yielding

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{E} & =\frac{V_{P}}{R_{E}}  \tag{5.51}\\
& =\frac{1}{R_{E}}\left(V_{C C} \frac{R_{2}}{R_{1}+R_{2}}-V_{B E}\right)  \tag{5.52}\\
& \approx I_{C}, \tag{5.53}
\end{align*}
$$

if $\beta \gg 1$. How can this result be less sensitive to variations in $V_{X}$ or $V_{B E}$? If the voltage drop across $R_{E}$, i.e., the difference between $V_{C C} R_{2} /\left(R_{1}+R_{2}\right)$ and $V_{B E}$, is sufficiently large to absorb and mitigate such variations, then $I_{E}$ and $I_{C}$ remain relatively stable. An example illustrates this concept.

Calculate the bias currents in the circuit of Fig. 5.20 and confirm that $Q_{1}$ operates in the forward active region. Assume $\beta=100$ and $I_{S}=5 \times 10^{-17} \mathrm{~A}$. How much does the collector current change if $R_{2}$ is $1 \%$ higher than its nominal value?
